      "title": "[PDF] TEXAS TIME OF USE RATE - Xcel Energy",
      "text": "TEXAS TIME OF USE RATE\nFREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS\nWhat is the Time of Use Rate and how does it work?\nThe Texas Time of Use (TOU) Rate is an optional rate that allows for a customer to be billed based on on\u0002peak and off-peaks periods. Under this rate, on-peak hours are from 1 p.m. to 7 p.m., Monday through\nFriday during the months of June through September. All other hours and months are considered off\u0002peak. Customers pay different energy charges based on the on-peak or off-peak periods in which energy\nis used. The rate has the potential to save customers money if they tend to use most of their electricity\nduring off-peak hours.\nWho is eligible for the TOU rate?\nTexas electric customers under the following rates are eligible for TOU: Residential Service, Small\nGeneral Service, Small Municipal and School Service, Large Municipal Service, Large School Service, and\nGeneral Service at Secondary and Primary voltage.\nHow are customers billed on this rate?\nDuring the months of June through Sep",
      "highlights": [
        " Under this rate, on-peak hours are from 1 p.m. to 7 p.m., Monday through Friday during the months of June through September. All other hours and months are considered off\u0002peak. Customers pay different energy charges based on the on-peak or off-peak periods in which energy  ...    during off-peak hours.\nWho is eligible for the TOU rate? Texas electric customers under the following rates are eligible for TOU: Residential Service, Small General Service, Small Municipal and School Service, Large Municipal Service, Large School Service, and  ...    During the months of June through September, a TOU customer will see an on-peak and off-peak energy charge on their electric bill. During the other months of the year, the customer will see the off-peak energy, or, if applicable, demand charge for all hours based on their TOU customer class. The TOU rate is  ...    Residential: $11.40 per month\nSmall General: $13.40 per month\nSmall Municipal and School: $17.51 per month Large  ...    What are the energy and demand charges associated with this rate? The following is the per kilowatt-hour energy charge, and demand charge if applicable, for customers on the TOU rate. On-peak hours are defined as 1 p.m. to 7 p.m., Monday through Friday, June through\nSeptember. Residential:\n$0.077926 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.167315 per kWh used during on-peak hours\nSmall General: $0.062040 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.187776 per kWh used during on-peak hours\nSmall Municipal and School: $0.044350 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.156399 per kWh used during on-peak hours\nLarge Municipal Secondary: $0.013698 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.165326 per kWh used during on-peak hours Demand charge: $10.01 per kW of demand used per month\nLarge Municipal Primary: $0.014136 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.156334 per kWh used during on-peak hours Demand charge: $9.71 per kW of demand used per month\nLarge School Secondary: $0.020273 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.180392 per kWh used during on-peak hours Demand charge: $12.40 per kW of demand used per month\nLarge School Primary: $0.019926 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.180045 per kWh used during on-peak hours Demand charge: $9.87 per kW of demand used per month\nSecondary General:\n$0.010016 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS $0.169056 per kWh used during on-peak hours\nDemand charge: $13.75 per kW of demand used per month\nPrimary General: $0.007740 per kWh used during all hours, PLUS\n$0.141482 per kWh used during on-peak hours Demand charge: $11.45 per kW of demand used per month\nIs there a minimum contract term? Customers must contract for service under this tariff for a minimum of 12 consecutive calendar months. A TOU customer will automatically remain on the rate unless they request to be taken off. How do I know if the rate is right for me? We recommend that you evaluate your energy usage and determine if you tend to use more energy during the off-peak times or you can shift your load to those times. On-peak"
